284:    "summary": "A pipeline step running `az boards`/`az repos` WITHOUT --organization/--project triggers the azure-devops CLI's git-remote context auto-detection: it reads `git config remote.origin.url` and calls `GET <org>/<project>/_git/<repo>/vsts/info` (cached in ~/.azure/azuredevops/cache/remotes.json). On an EPHEMERAL Microsoft-hosted agent the cache is ALWAYS cold, so the call fires every run. Under the project setting enforceJobAuthScope=true the project-scoped Build Service token (System.AccessToken) is denied that repo-context read -> `TF401019: The Git repository ... does not exist or you do not have permissions ... 404` (a 404-masks-403). The lowercased repo id in the error == the /vsts/info URL repo id, byte-for-byte. This makes a *Boards* command emit a *git-repository* error even though tagging never reads the repo. Switching the agent pool does NOT fix it: the auth identity is the project Build Service identity, INDEPENDENT of the pool (a pool swap only masks via a different az/extension version or a cached broad credential, and costs a second runner + job split).",
285-    "root_cause": "The CLI's implicit context auto-detection is a privileged repo-context read; under a scoped pipeline token it is denied. The script relied on auto-detection instead of explicit context. Onset is external (no code change): a long-static script breaks when enforceJobAuthScope is enabled or the hosted agent's az/azure-devops extension version starts performing the cold-cache /vsts/info detection.",
286-    "fix": "Pass explicit, detection-free context: `az boards query --organization \"$SYSTEM_COLLECTIONURI\" --project \"$SYSTEM_TEAMPROJECT\" --detect false`. The /vsts/info call then never happens (verified: `--debug | grep -c vsts/info` = 0). NOTE: `az boards work-item show/update` accept --org/--detect but REJECT --project (work items are org-global by id: `unrecognized arguments: --project`) -- use two contexts. Only `az boards query` needs the fix (work-item show/update never call /vsts/info). Do NOT 'switch to the Core Platform runner' as the fix. Triage: (1) `az repos show` proves the repo exists -> it's permission, not missing; (2) is the failing call an az boards/az repos call without --org? (3) `az devops invoke build generalSettings --query enforceJobAuthScope`.",
