302:    "summary": "GREEN step != realized effect. A bash pipeline step with no `set -e` that runs a command inside a process substitution (`while read ...; do ...; done < <(cmd)`) SWALLOWS cmd's non-zero exit, so the ADO task succeeds while the work silently never happened (BTM: `az boards query` returned TF401019, the tag was never applied, build stayed green for ~6 weeks). Detection/fix: verify the REALIZED effect (the tag/resource/state), never the step status. Two more reusable moves from this incident: (a) DATE a silent onset by bisecting historical build logs for the error string -- `az devops invoke build builds maxTime=<date> ... resultFilter=succeeded` -> timeline -> the step's log -> grep; this turned 'weeks or months ago' into a 10-day window (2026-04-15 OK -> 04-25 broken) and, with no code change in that window, proved an external/org trigger. (b) For a COSMETIC post-deploy step (no continueOnError) make failures loud-but-NON-blocking via `echo ##vso[task.logissue type=error]` + `##vso[task.complete result=SucceededWithIssues]` -- a bare `set -euo pipefail` would convert a transient WIT 5xx or a future cross-project item into a deploy-blocking RED build.",
303-    "root_cause": "Process substitution runs in a child whose exit code does not propagate to the parent; without set -e the parent exits 0. The original also clobbered tags: a flat `az boards query` returns only System.Id (no System.Tags), so the old `read -r id tags` got tags='' and wrote `System.Tags=; TAG`, replacing the tag list -- harmless only because BtM items had no other tags.",
304-    "fix": "Capture command output into a variable (so set -e / explicit check can catch failure) instead of piping into a process substitution; assert the realized effect in verification; read-modify-write the UNION for additive fields (System.Tags), never overwrite; use SucceededWithIssues for non-blocking visibility on cosmetic steps. Onset-bisection one-liner template lives in the incident's rca.md L11.",
