# FBE Fix And Knowledge Discipline

## Fix Gate

Before executing or prescribing a fix:

1. Prove the class with at least three surfaces or label it A3.
2. Verify the recipe or pattern status in `fbe-errors/_index.md`.
3. Confirm Sandbox subscription and target slot.
4. Check Terraform state blob lease and concurrent pipeline runs if Terraform
   state or Azure resources are touched.
5. For any destructive command, ask the user for explicit authorization naming
   the exact command scope and irreversibility.

## Name-Guarded Destruction

Destructive commands must fail closed on target mismatch:

```bash
TARGET="vpp-evh-premium-kidu"
case "$TARGET" in
  vpp-evh-premium-kidu) ;;
  *) echo "Refusing unexpected target: $TARGET" >&2; exit 1 ;;
esac
```

The guard must include the literal intended target, not a broad wildcard that
would also match production or another slot.

## Polling Loop Discipline

Do not use this pattern:

```bash
until ! az resource show ... >/dev/null 2>&1; do sleep 5; done
```

It treats auth failures, throttling, DNS failures, and real deletion as the
same success. Poll stderr and discriminate `ResourceNotFound` from other
errors. On any non-not-found error, stop and print the captured stderr.

## Required Pre-Rerun Checks

Before rerunning pipeline 2412 after a fix:

- The target Azure resource is gone or patched as expected.
- The Terraform state blob lease is not locked.
- No pipeline 2412 run is already in progress for the same branch.
- The lease table still maps the slot to the expected branch.
- GitOps state is fresh enough for the route.

## Non-Negotiable Anti-Patterns

- Do not use pipeline 2629 destroy as rollback for stuck create.
- Do not silently retry a pipeline with the same underlying defect.
- Do not mask environmental defects with `lifecycle.ignore_changes`.
- Do not use broad `NoWarn` to hide NuGet CVEs unless the reviewed recipe
  explicitly authorizes a scoped bridge and names its expiry.
- Do not trust stale local clones.
- Do not expose PATs or secrets in output, logs, chat, or markdown artifacts.

## Knowledge Writeback

Every non-trivial incident writes four artifacts under:

```text
$SECOND_BRAIN_PATH/2-areas/work-eneco/eneco-vpp-platform/fbe-errors/
```

Use these names:

```text
YYYY-MM-DD-{slot-or-class}-{shortname}-rca.md
YYYY-MM-DD-{slot-or-class}-{shortname}-fix.md
YYYY-MM-DD-{slot-or-class}-{shortname}-explanation.md
YYYY-MM-DD-{slot-or-class}-{shortname}-lessons.md
```

Render templates with computed dates before creating notes:

```bash
std/skills/10_employer/eneco/eneco-fbe-troubleshoot/scripts/render-fbe-incident-templates.sh \
  "$SECOND_BRAIN_PATH/2-areas/work-eneco/eneco-vpp-platform/fbe-errors" \
  "YYYY-MM-DD-{slot-or-class}-{shortname}" \
  "{Incident title}"
```

This avoids raw `{{YYYY-MM-DD}}` and `{{YYYY-MM-DD_PLUS_3_MONTHS}}`
placeholders in Knowledge DNA frontmatter. Raw placeholders are rejected by
freshness audits even if the Markdown otherwise looks complete.

Also update `_index.md` symptom matrix and incident table.

Use:

- `2ndbrain-obsidian` for navigation, filenames, and vault-native operations.
- `2ndbrain-knowledge-build` for note creation, frontmatter, A1/A2/A3 labels,
  backlinks, and Knowledge DNA consistency.

## Promotion Gate

New or changed pattern/recipe pages start as `status: review` unless they are
pure incident records with no reusable remediation claim.

Before `status: active`:

1. Dispatch `socrates-contrarian` against discriminator uniqueness and hidden
   assumptions.
2. Dispatch `el-demoledor` against command safety, live-environment failure
   modes, and false-positive verification.
3. Wait for both.
4. Patch once, with receipts.
5. If either verdict is reject, leave `status: review`, add `review_reason`,
   and flag the `_index.md` row.
6. If either reviewer is unavailable, leave `status: review` and record
   `UNVERIFIED[blocked]` with the missing reviewer, blocked claim, and promotion
   path.

The NuGet CVE class is the cautionary precedent: symptom recognition is useful,
but remediation routes remain untrusted after adversarial rejection.

## ArgoCD Tool Auth Ladder

If the normal ArgoCD CLI session is expired, do not stop at "user must log in".
The CLI can run in `--core` mode using the current Kubernetes context.

```bash
# Clear stale SSO config only after recording the old path.
mv ~/.config/argocd/config ~/.config/argocd/config.bak.$(date +%s)

# Let argocd --core find argocd-cm.
kubectl config set-context --current --namespace=argocd
# Or: export ARGOCD_NAMESPACE=argocd

argocd repocreds list --core
argocd repo list --core
argocd app list --core
```

| Operation | Preferred | If primary fails | Fallback |
|---|---|---|---|
| Read Application status | `argocd app get --core` | AppProject RBAC may deny per-App reads | `kubectl get application -n <ns> <name> -o yaml` |
| List Applications cluster-wide | `kubectl get applications.argoproj.io -A` | None expected with cluster-admin context | Same |
| List repositories/templates | `argocd repo list --core`, `argocd repocreds list --core` | Expired cached SSO config | Move config aside and retry `--core`; then inspect Secrets |
| Add new credential template | `argocd repocreds add --core <URL> --username <U> --password <P>` | CLI unavailable | ArgoCD UI Credentials Template; last resort raw Secret YAML |
| Patch existing repo Secret password | `kubectl patch secret <name> -n argocd --type=json ...` | None | Recreate through controlled Secret path |
| Trigger refresh | Natural reconcile first | Need targeted refresh | `argocd app get --core <app> --refresh`; fallback refresh annotation |

## Apply Surface Decision

Pick the mutation surface from the change type, not from habit:

| Change kind | Preferred surface | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| Add a new credential template | `argocd repocreds add --core <URL> --username <U> --password <P>` or ArgoCD UI Credentials Template | ArgoCD validates the repo-creds shape and stores the right secret contract. |
| Patch an existing credential Secret password | `kubectl patch secret <name> -n argocd --type=json ...` | The CLI adds/removes repo credentials; it is not the natural editor for an existing Secret's password field. |
| Inspect credential coverage | `argocd repocreds list --core` plus `kubectl get secret ...` | The CLI shows ArgoCD's view; raw Secrets show exact URL byte form. |
| Emergency fallback when ArgoCD CLI/UI are unavailable | Raw Kubernetes Secret YAML | Last resort only; prove labels, `stringData`/base64 fields, and URL form against a working sibling first. |

## Deployment Contract And Rollout Tier

Mutation scope follows the environment contract.

| Environment | Contract | Default rollout |
|---|---|---|
| Sandbox FBE | Ephemeral, GitOps source-of-truth, high churn; manual drift in slot namespaces is not normally protected | Tier 1 minimal: read-only baseline, one credential/template fix, natural reconcile, consumer-surface verification |
| dev-MC / acc-MC / prd-MC | Stable environments; manual operator intervention can be deliberate | Tier 2 throttled: consider disabling prune/selfHeal, review diffs, re-enable per app after approval |

Tier 1 minimal for Sandbox FBE:

1. Baseline broken Application count, healthy count, and critical monitoring
   object count.
2. Apply one credential template or one existing-secret rotation.
3. Wait for natural reconcile. Do not restart repo-server or application
   controller by default.
4. Verify broken count trends to zero and no bystander regression appears.

Tier 2 throttled is an escalation path when Tier 1 stalls for five minutes,
repo-server CPU saturates, PrometheusRule or bystander app counts regress, or
the environment contract requires drift preservation.

## Credential Intake Conventions

Prefer credential sources that keep secret bytes out of chat and logs:

1. In-cluster existing working Secret: copy the PAT from a proven ArgoCD
   repository Secret only when the same identity is acceptable.
2. 1Password CLI: use the user's active `op` session and known Eneco service
   account items when available.
3. Operator-staged `.env.tmp`: first run a structure-only key-name probe and
   verify the file is ignored or untracked before reading values; delete it
   after use.
4. Manual paste in chat: last resort only.

Never echo PAT bytes to stdout, logs, RCA text, task files, or chat. Do not
commit `.env` files. Prefer stdin-capable secret entry; if a CLI only accepts a
positional secret, record the exposure risk and scrub shell history when
applicable.

## Knowledge Writeback: Seven Vault Surfaces

Every non-trivial FBE incident produces or updates seven vault surfaces under
`fbe-errors/`:

- Full RCA: 12-level ladder from business purpose to one-page playbook. Use
  `assets/templates/fbe-incident-rca.md.tmpl`.
- Executable fix procedure: commands, gates, expected outputs, rollback, and
  anti-patterns. Use `assets/templates/fbe-incident-fix.md.tmpl`.
- Recreation guide: prerequisites, source inventory, replay probes, expected
  outputs, and evidence-promotion rules so another human or agent can recreate
  the diagnosis. Use `assets/templates/fbe-incident-recreate.md.tmpl`.
- SRE toil-removal proposal: automation/removal/shift-left/alert/ownership
  options grounded in the RCA, with ROI and failure-mode critique. Use
  `assets/templates/fbe-incident-toil-removal-proposal.md.tmpl`.
- Natural-language explanation: one paragraph for the affected developer. Use
  `assets/templates/fbe-incident-explanation.md.tmpl`.
- Distilled lessons: stripped of incident-specific nouns. Use
  `assets/templates/fbe-incident-lessons.md.tmpl`.
- `_index.md`: symptom matrix and incident table entry.

Render the six templates with concrete dates before writing vault notes:

```bash
std/skills/10_employer/eneco/eneco-fbe-troubleshoot/scripts/render-fbe-incident-templates.sh \
  "$SECOND_BRAIN_PATH/2-areas/work-eneco/eneco-vpp-platform/fbe-errors" \
  "YYYY-MM-DD-{slot-or-class}-{shortname}" \
  "{Incident title}"
```

The renderer computes `created`, `updated`, `last_validated`, and
`review_after` (`today + 3 months`) using macOS `date -v+3m` or GNU
`date -d '+3 months'`. Do not copy raw templates directly into the vault; raw
`{{YYYY-MM-DD}}` placeholders make freshness audits lie.

For the Application source-N credential coverage class, the required vault
writeback set is:

| Artifact | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `pattern-argocd-per-application-source-credential-gap.md` | Explain exact Repository vs longest-prefix `repo-creds` resolution and why this is distinct from ApplicationSet PAT expiry. |
| `recipe-register-missing-credential-template.md` | Probe coverage, add the missing template, and verify consumer-surface recovery. |
| `YYYY-MM-DD-{slot}-source1-credential-gap.md` | Incident page linking the RCA, fix, recreate guide, and toil proposal. |
| `fbe-errors/_index.md` row | Route `ApplicationSet healthy + source-N auth ComparisonError` to this pattern and recipe. |
| `recipe-rotate-argocd-sandbox-pat.md` Step 7 amendment | Add per-Application source-fetch verification so PAT rotation cannot stop one layer too high. |

Until these vault artifacts exist and are reviewed, the router returns
`status=review` for the source-N class. Recognition is allowed; blind execution
as an active recipe is not.

Invoke `2ndbrain-obsidian` for vault navigation and `2ndbrain-knowledge-build`
for note creation so frontmatter, filenames, backlinks, A1/A2/A3 labels, and
mutation ledgers match the existing catalogue.

Before promoting a pattern or recipe to `status: active`, dispatch
`socrates-contrarian` and `el-demoledor` in parallel. If either rejects, keep
the note at `status: review`, add `review_reason`, and flag the index entry.
If either reviewer is unavailable in the runtime, do not substitute self-review;
keep `status: review` and record `UNVERIFIED[blocked]` with the missing
reviewer and affected claim.

